******
[2] New Mexico
Date: Fri 22 Mar 2019
Source: CBS 4 Local [edited]
https://cbs4local.com/news/local/some-prisoners-quarantined-in-otero-county-prison-to-stop-spread-of-chickenpox


Health officials at a prison in southern New Mexico are working to stop the spread of chickenpox. Some inmates at the Otero County prison have been placed in quarantine. The prison said one inmate was diagnosed with chickenpox and staff acted quickly as a precaution.

As of Thursday [21 Mar 2019] , there is only one confirmed case. Just off Highway 54 in New Mexico, you can see some inmates out enjoying a sunny spring day. What you don't see is others in isolation who may have been exposed to chickenpox.

Chantel Virammontes lives just up the street from the prison. "I've seen things go and come out here in Chaparral," said Virammontes. "Probably about a mile. Sounds very extreme, it's scary."

Jeff Gore agrees but says he's glad the prison is doing what it feels is needed. "Well, if it's necessary from keeping it from getting spread, it's the right thing to do," said Gore.

Gore told CBS4 he knows various people throughout the Chapparal community who work in the prison. "It still could possibly get spread to one of the guards, and one of the guards could spread it to the community," said Gore.

The prison said it has several housing units quarantined but didn't say how many or the number of prisoners that includes. The prison said visitors are still allowed on the weekends. Some of those inmates have been isolated for 11 days now.

[Byline: Jala Washington]

